 surrounding areas after you are in Nainital is on foot. Naini Lake is close to the Nainital Bus Stand, which may be reached on foot. 5. Snow View Point Snow View Point in Nainital, located 2270 meters above sea level, is one of the most famous tourist spots in the region. Snow Picture Point provides a panoramic view of the milky-white Himalayas. A wonderful combination of binoculars has been put at the Snow View Point, allowing you to get up close and personal with the Himalayan ranges and their majestic peaks. A small temple with images of Rama, Sita, Lakshmana, Hanuman, Durga, and Shiva may be found if you look closely. Snow View Point is situated above Mall Road in Mallital. It offers an impressive perspective of the snow-capped Himalayas, including important peaks like Nanda Devi, Nanda Kot, and Trishul. The aerial cable car is the best way to get to this area. Adults pay Rs 80 for a one-way ropeway ticket to Snow View Point, while children pay Rs 40. The greatest time to visit Snow View Point in Nainital is during the summer, from mid-March to mid-April, when the temperature ranges from 10°C to 27°C. 6. Naina Devi Temple Naina Devi Temple in Nainital is a popular Hindu worship destination and one of India's fifty-one Shakti Peethas. Naina Devi Temple is one of North India's most famous temples. Inside the Naina Devi Temple, the roof has two eyes representing Goddess Naina Devi, with idols of Goddess Kali and Lord Ganesha in between. The best time to visit Naina Devi Temple is during Navratri, which takes place from September to October, Shravani Mela, which takes place from July to August, and Chaitra Mela, which takes place from March to April. The Nainital city is named after the Naina Devi temple. The Naina Devi temple is said to have been constructed on the location where the goddess's eyes are said to have dropped as Lord Vishnu chopped off her body with his Sudarshana. This location is within a few meters of the Nainital Bus Station. Various stores selling prasad and other essential puja items will greet you as you approach the hill to the temple. To get to the Naina Devi Temple from other parts of town, take a cab or take a taxi. 7. Kainchi Dham Kanchi Dham, located on the Nainital-Almora route, is a small ashram and Hanuman temple. Kanchi Dham is another name for Neem Karoli Baba Ashram. This beautiful temple was established by Shri Neem Karoli Baba Maharaj Ji, a Hindu Guru. He was a devotee of Lord Hanuman and was known for performing countless miracles during his life. Sri Maa, Neem Karoli Baba's major disciple, currently oversees the ashram, which is only available to guests while she is present. Because it is hidden in the mountains and surrounded by beautiful greenery, Neem Karoli Baba Ashram is the ultimate place to experience silence and peace. This ashram at Kanchi Dham can also accommodate devotees. In the ashram, Hanuman Chalisa is recited numerous times during the day. On June 15, the temple hosts a large fair that residents and foreigners visit annually. 8. Naina Peak Naina Peak, at 2615 meters, is the highest point in Nainital. It is a major tourist attraction of the city and is covered in snow all year. There is a beautiful view from the shade of trees above it. From the top of this peak, you can see the Nanda Devi peak and the mountains of Tibet. The well-known location is one of the most popular vacation destinations in Nainital. The landscape of Naina Peak may be viewed from a variety of perspectives. Aside from trekking, guests may also ride a pony to the top of the mountain. A journey to Nainital isn't complete without walking the 6 kilometres from Mallital to the peak of Naina Peak. The journey is one of the most popular among Nainital visitors. Because Nainital is a hill station, it is best to come during the summer. For tourists, the months of March through June are good for camping and local sightseeing. Naina Peak is around 17 kilometres from Nainital's Tallital Bus Stand. To get to Tallital, take a private or shared cab or passenger car. 9. Bhimtal Lake Bhimtal Lake is one of India's most well-known lakes, located near the city of Bhimtal in the northern Indian state of Uttarakhand. Bhimtal Lake is the largest lake in the Kumaon region, often known as India's Lake District, and serves as a source of drinking water for the city. The lake has been given access to tourists, and various activities occur in and around it. The area around Bhimtal Lake is carefully maintained and offers a nice experience to everyone who visits. Bhimtal Lake Aquarium is on a tiny island in the heart of Bhimtal Lake's beautiful waters. The aquarium contains roughly 12 huge tanks and a variety of species. After the Anglo-Nepal War, the British Raj constructed the Bhimtal Lake Dam in 1883. In the 17th century, Raja Baj Bahadur Chand of the Kumaon Kingdom constructed a shrine on the dam's banks. Boating on the calm waters of Bhimtal Lake is a pastime that everyone should try. The panoramic picture of the lake's beautiful waters beneath lush trees and pure blue skies is magnificent. Boating is accessible daily from 9:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. for INR 150 per person. The picturesque Bhimtal Lake is accessible by private or public transportation from everywhere in Bhimtal. 10. Astronomical Observatory If astronomy is something that fascinates you and is on your wishlist, visits the Nainital Astronomical Observatory. The observatory was established on April 20, 1954. On March 22, 2004, the 50-year-old state observatory at Nainital was renamed ARIES, an acronym for Aryabhatta Research Institute of Observation-Sciences, an independent institute under the Government and Department of Science and Technology. The Aryabhata Research Institute of Observational Science is located 9 kilometres south of the city on Manora Peak, 1951, meters above sea level. Visitors to this Nainital site may observe the Moon, stars, and other celestial bodies through four powerful telescopes. Plan a time window and seek permission from the authorities before visiting this place. 11. Hanuman Garhi About 3.5 kilometres from Nainital. Baba Neem Karoli Ji founded the Hanuman Garhi temple in 1950 AD, which is around 1,951 meters (6,400 feet) above sea level. Along with Hanuman Ji, there are monuments of many other gods and goddesses at the Hanuman Garhi temple, the names of which are mentioned are- Lord Rama, Mata Sita, Shri Krishna Bhagwan, Radha, Lord Shiva, Maa Durga, Sai Baba, Neem Karoli Baba, Vaishno Devi, Mouni Mai, and Shani Dev, among others, are worshipped in the Hanuman Garhi temple. 12. Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple is located in the Nainital district, at the highest point of Mukteshwar city in the Kumaon mountains, at approximately 7,595 feet (2,315 meters above sea level). Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple had a 350-year history when it was known as Lord Shiva, but it is now known as Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple or Mukteshwar Temple. To get the darshan of Lord Shiva built in Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple, you must climb around 100 stairs. 13. Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple is located around 22 kilometres from Nainital, Uttarakhand. It is situated on the borders of Bhimtal Lake. People believe that Bhima, the most powerful of the Pandavas, established this temple of Lord Shiva after performing penance to Lord Shiva for his clan's name to be remembered for ages. Throughout the year, people go to the temple of Lord Shiva. 14. Jim Corbett National Park Jim Corbett National Park, in Nainital in Uttarakhand, was established in 1936 to save the Bengal Tiger. When Jim Corbett National Park was established in 1936, it was named "Haley National Park." After that, it was renamed Ramganga in 1952 and Jim Corbett National Park in 1956, and this national park was renamed after the hunter and naturalist Jim Corbett The Bengal Tiger, Cheetah, Leopard, Elephant, Bear, Wild Boar, Deer, Sambar, Nilgai, Gharial, Monitor Lizard, Viper, and King Cobra, may be