ssive perspective of the snow-capped Himalayas, including important peaks like Nanda Devi, Nanda Kot, and Trishul. The aerial cable car is the best way to get to this area. Adults pay Rs 80 for a one-way ropeway ticket to Snow View Point, while children pay Rs 40. The greatest time to visit Snow View Point in Nainital is during the summer, from mid-March to mid-April, when the temperature ranges from 10°C to 27°C. 6. Naina Devi Temple Naina Devi Temple in Nainital is a popular Hindu worship destination and one of India's fifty-one Shakti Peethas. Naina Devi Temple is one of North India's most famous temples. Inside the Naina Devi Temple, the roof has two eyes representing Goddess Naina Devi, with idols of Goddess Kali and Lord Ganesha in between. The best time to visit Naina Devi Temple is during Navratri, which takes place from September to October, Shravani Mela, which takes place from July to August, and Chaitra Mela, which takes place from March to April. The Nainital city is named after the Naina Devi temple. The Naina Devi temple is said to have been constructed on the location where the goddess's eyes are said to have dropped as Lord Vishnu chopped off her body with his Sudarshana. This location is within a few meters of the Nainital Bus Station. Various stores selling prasad and other essential puja items will greet you as you approach the hill to the temple. To get to the Naina Devi Temple from other parts of town, take a cab or take a taxi. 7. Kainchi Dham Kanchi Dham, located on the Nainital-Almora route, is a small ashram and Hanuman temple. Kanchi Dham is another name for Neem Karoli Baba Ashram. This beautiful temple was established by Shri Neem Karoli Baba Maharaj Ji, a Hindu Guru. He was a devotee of Lord Hanuman and was known for performing countless miracles during his life. Sri Maa, Neem Karoli Baba's major disciple, currently oversees the ashram, which is only available to guests while she is present. Because it is hidden in the mountains and sur