e without walking the 6 kilometres from Mallital to the peak of Naina Peak. The journey is one of the most popular among Nainital visitors. Because Nainital is a hill station, it is best to come during the summer. For tourists, the months of March through June are good for camping and local sightseeing. Naina Peak is around 17 kilometres from Nainital's Tallital Bus Stand. To get to Tallital, take a private or shared cab or passenger car. 9. Bhimtal Lake Bhimtal Lake is one of India's most well-known lakes, located near the city of Bhimtal in the northern Indian state of Uttarakhand. Bhimtal Lake is the largest lake in the Kumaon region, often known as India's Lake District, and serves as a source of drinking water for the city. The lake has been given access to tourists, and various activities occur in and around it. The area around Bhimtal Lake is carefully maintained and offers a nice experience to everyone who visits. Bhimtal Lake Aquarium is on a tiny island in the heart of Bhimtal Lake's beautiful waters. The aquarium contains roughly 12 huge tanks and a variety of species. After the Anglo-Nepal War, the British Raj constructed the Bhimtal Lake Dam in 1883. In the 17th century, Raja Baj Bahadur Chand of the Kumaon Kingdom constructed a shrine on the dam's banks. Boating on the calm waters of Bhimtal Lake is a pastime that everyone should try. The panoramic picture of the lake's beautiful waters beneath lush trees and pure blue skies is magnificent. Boating is accessible daily from 9:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. for INR 150 per person. The picturesque Bhimtal Lake is accessible by private or public transportation from everywhere in Bhimtal. 10. Astronomical Observatory If astronomy is something that fascinates you and is on your wishlist, visits the Nainital Astronomical Observatory. The observatory was established on April 20, 1954. On March 22, 2004, the 50-year-old state observatory at Nainital was renamed ARIES, an acronym for Aryabhatta Research Institute of Observation-Sciences, an independent institute under the Government and Department of Science and Technology. The Aryabhata Research Institute of Observational Science is located 9 kilometres south of the city on Manora Peak, 1951, meters above sea level. Visitors to this Nainital site may observe the Moon, stars, and other celestial bodies through four powerful telescopes. Plan a time window and seek permission from the authorities before visiting this place. 11. Hanuman Garhi About 3.5 kilometres from Nainital. Baba Neem Karoli Ji founded the Hanuman Garhi temple in 1950 AD, which is around 1,951 meters (6,400 feet) above sea level. Along with Hanuman Ji, there are monuments of many other gods and goddesses at the Hanuman Garhi temple, the names of which are mentioned are- Lord Rama, Mata Sita, Shri Krishna Bhagwan, Radha, Lord Shiva, Maa Durga, Sai Baba, Neem Karoli Baba, Vaishno Devi, Mouni Mai, and Shani Dev, among others, are worshipped in the Hanuman Garhi temple. 12. Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple is located in the Nainital district, at the highest point of Mukteshwar city in the Kumaon mountains, at approximately 7,595 feet (2,315 meters above sea level). Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple had a 350-year history when it was known as Lord Shiva, but it is now known as Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple or Mukteshwar Temple. To get the darshan of Lord Shiva built in Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple, you must climb around 100 stairs. 13. Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple is located around 22 kilometres from Nainital, Uttarakhand. It is situated on the borders of Bhimtal Lake. People believe that Bhima, the most powerful of the Pandavas, established this temple of Lord Shiva after performing penance to Lord Shiva for his clan's name to be remembered for ages. Throughout the year, people go to the temple of Lord Shiva. 14. Jim Corbett National Park Jim Corbett National Park, in Nainital in Uttarakhand, was established in 1936 to save the Bengal Tiger. W