rant at the top of the hill, Dorothy's Seat. On clear days, the amazing view of Nanda Devi may also be viewed. Tiffin Top's wonderful view makes it an ideal place for an adventurous journey. The surrounding peaks of the Aryapatta hills and the lovely landscape of Nainital make it a popular destination for both residents and visitors. Dorothy Kellett, an English painter who used to sit and paint here, inspired the name. Tiffin Top is located 4 kilometres from Nainital. One may hike for around 10 kilometres, going past Ayarapatta's Sherwood School and down from Bada Patthar. Another option is to hire a horse from Bada Patthar, which would cost around Rs 700 per person. 4. Nainital Lake Nainital Lake, also known as Naini Lake, is a natural freshwater lake in the Kumaon town of Nainital. Naini Peak in the northwest, Tiffin Point in the southwest, and Nainital Lake in the north, all surrounded by snow-capped hills, offer spectacular vistas, particularly at sunrise and sunset. It is well known for boats, picnics, and night walks. Naini Lake, formerly a lovely lake loved by Europeans, is now a popular tourist attraction for visitors from all over the country. The natural beauty of this place is enhanced by the coniferous trees that blanket the slope. Nainital Mall Road, the city's main shopping area, runs along to Naini Lake and is a must-see for every shopper. A trip to Naini Lake would be incomplete if one did not go boating. The easiest method to view Naini Lake and the surrounding areas after you are in Nainital is on foot. Naini Lake is close to the Nainital Bus Stand, which may be reached on foot. 5. Snow View Point Snow View Point in Nainital, located 2270 meters above sea level, is one of the most famous tourist spots in the region. Snow Picture Point provides a panoramic view of the milky-white Himalayas. A wonderful combination of binoculars has been put at the Snow View Point, allowing you to get up close and personal with the Himalayan ranges and their majestic peaks. A small temple with images of Rama, Sita, Lakshmana, Hanuman, Durga, and Shiva may be found if you look closely. Snow View Point is situated above Mall Road in Mallital. It offers an impressive perspective of the snow-capped Himalayas, including important peaks like Nanda Devi, Nanda Kot, and Trishul. The aerial cable car is the best way to get to this area. Adults pay Rs 80 for a one-way ropeway ticket to Snow View Point, while children pay Rs 40. The greatest time to visit Snow View Point in Nainital is during the summer, from mid-March to mid-April, when the temperature ranges from 10°C to 27°C. 6. Naina Devi Temple Naina Devi Temple in Nainital is a popular Hindu worship destination and one of India's fifty-one Shakti Peethas. Naina Devi Temple is one of North India's most famous temples. Inside the Naina Devi Temple, the roof has two eyes representing Goddess Naina Devi, with idols of Goddess Kali and Lord Ganesha in between. The best time to visit Naina Devi Temple is during Navratri, which takes place from September to October, Shravani Mela, which takes place from July to August, and Chaitra Mela, which takes place from March to April. The Nainital city is named after the Naina Devi temple. The Naina Devi temple is said to have been constructed on the location where the goddess's eyes are said to have dropped as Lord Vishnu chopped off her body with his Sudarshana. This location is within a few meters of the Nainital Bus Station. Various stores selling prasad and other essential puja items will greet you as you approach the hill to the temple. To get to the Naina Devi Temple from other parts of town, take a cab or take a taxi. 7. Kainchi Dham Kanchi Dham, located on the Nainital-Almora route, is a small ashram and Hanuman temple. Kanchi Dham is another name for Neem Karoli Baba Ashram. This beautiful temple was established by Shri Neem Karoli Baba Maharaj Ji, a Hindu Guru. He was a devotee of Lord Hanuman and was known for performing countless miracles during his life. Sri Maa, Neem Karoli Baba's major disciple, currently oversees the ashram, which is only available to guests while she is present. Because it is hidden in the mountains and surrounded by beautiful greenery, Neem Karoli Baba Ashram is the ultimate place to experience silence and peace. This ashram at Kanchi Dham can also accommodate devotees. In the ashram, Hanuman Chalisa is recited numerous times during the day. On June 15, the temple hosts a large fair that residents and foreigners visit annually. 8. Naina Peak Naina Peak, at 2615 meters, is the highest point in Nainital. It is a major tourist attraction of the city and is covered in snow all year. There is a beautiful view from the shade of trees above it. From the top of this peak, you can see the Nanda Devi peak and the mountains of Tibet. The well-known location is one of the most popular vacation destinations in Nainital. The landscape of Naina Peak may be viewed from a variety of perspectives. Aside from trekking, guests may also ride a pony to the top of the mountain. A journey to Nainital isn't complete without walking the 6 kilometres from Mallital to the peak of Naina Peak. The journey is one of the most popular among Nainital visitors. Because Nainital is a hill station, it is best to come during the summer. For tourists, the months of March through June are good for camping and local sightseeing. Naina Peak is around 17 kilometres from Nainital's Tallital Bus Stand. To get to Tallital, take a private or shared cab or passenger car. 9. Bhimtal Lake Bhimtal Lake is one of India's most well-known lakes, located near the city of Bhimtal in the northern Indian state of Uttarakhand. Bhimtal Lake is the largest lake in the Kumaon region, often known as India's Lake District, and serves as a source of drinking water for the city. The lake has been given access to tourists, and various activities occur in and around it. The area around Bhimtal Lake is carefully maintained and offers a nice e