o Cave Garden was created to provide tourists with a view of Himalayan wildlife's natural environment by creating various curves for different animals to return home. The Eco Cave Garden is about 1 kilometre from Mall Road and easily accessible on foot. Otherwise, you may take a taxi. 2. Mall Road The British built Nainital's Mall Road, formally known as Govind Ballabh Pant Marg. The Nainital Mall Road connects the hill town of Mallital with the two ends of Tallital, the primary shopping, eating, and cultural centre of wonder in Nainital. There are several hotels, showrooms, department stores, and businesses on Mall Road. Restaurants and cafes are available. Mall Road is home to some of the greatest hotels and restaurants in Nainital. During the day, it is one of the busiest and most crowded locations. A night walk around the mall has its special beauty, with the cold wind coming across the road through the lake. It is a famous tourist location with a wonderful view of Nainital Lake. An interesting fact about this location is that it was used to film several famous Bollywood movies, including "Kati Patang" and "Koi Mil Gaya". It is one of the most popular tourist attractions in Nainital. 3. Tiffin Top Tiffin Top, also known as Dorothy's Seat, is a well-known tourist attraction in Nainital. This is a wonderful picnic area to enjoy a beautiful view of Nainital. Cher, Oak, and Deodar trees cover the beautiful Tiffin Top. When viewed from here, the Naini Lake and the Kumaon hills are lovely. Tiffin Top was called for the restaurant at the top of the hill, Dorothy's Seat. On clear days, the amazing view of Nanda Devi may also be viewed. Tiffin Top's wonderful view makes it an ideal place for an adventurous journey. The surrounding peaks of the Aryapatta hills and the lovely landscape of Nainital make it a popular destination for both residents and visitors. Dorothy Kellett, an English painter who used to sit and paint here, inspired the name. Tiffin Top is located 4 kilometres from Nainital. One may hike for around 10 kilometres, going past Ayarapatta's Sherwood School and down from Bada Patthar. Another option is to hire a horse from Bada Patthar, which would cost around Rs 700 per person. 4. Nainital Lake Nainital Lake, also known as Naini Lake, is a natural freshwater lake in the Kumaon town of Nainital. Naini Peak in the northwest, Tiffin Point in the southwest, and Nainital Lake in the north, all surrounded by snow-capped hills, offer spectacular vistas, particularly at sunrise and sunset. It is well known for boats, picnics, and night walks. Naini Lake, formerly a lovely lake loved by Europeans, is now a popular tourist attraction for visitors from all over the country. The natural beauty of this place is enhanced by the coniferous trees that blanket the slope. Nainital Mall Road, the city's main shopping area, runs along to Naini Lake and is a must-see for every shopper. A trip to Naini Lake would be incomplete if one did not go boating. The easiest method to view Naini Lake and the surrounding areas after you are in Nainital is on foot. Naini Lake is close to the Nainital Bus Stand, which may be reached on foot. 5. Snow View Point Snow View Point in Nainital, located 2270 meters above sea level, is one of the most famous tourist spots in the region. Snow Picture Point provides a panoramic view of the milky-white Himalayas. A wonderful combination of binoculars has been put at the Snow View Point, allowing you to get up close and personal with the Himalayan ranges and their majestic peaks. A small temple with images of Rama, Sita, Lakshmana, Hanuman, Durga, and Shiva may be found if you look closely. Snow View Point is situated above Mall Road in Mallital. It offers an impressive perspective of the snow-capped Himalayas, including important peaks like Nanda Devi, Nanda Kot, and Trishul. The aerial cable car is the best way to get to this area. Adults pay Rs 80 for a one-way ropeway ticket to Snow View Point, while children pay Rs 40. The greatest time to visit Snow View Point in Nainital is during the summer, from mid-March to mid-April, when the temperature ranges from 10°C to 27°C. 6. Naina Devi Temple Naina Devi Temple in Nainital is a popular Hindu worship destination and one of India's fifty-one Shakti Peethas. Naina Devi Temple is one of North India's most famous temples. Inside the Naina Devi Temple, the roof has two eyes representing Goddess Naina Devi, with idols of Goddess Kali and Lord Ganesha in between. The best time to visit Naina Devi Temple is during Navratri, which takes place from September to October, Shravani Mela, which takes place from July to August, and Chaitra Mela, which takes place from March to April. The Nainital city is named after the Naina Devi temple. The Naina Devi temple is said to have been constructed on the location where the goddess's eyes are said to have dropped as Lord Vishnu chopped off her body with his Sudarshana. This location is within a few meters of the Nainital Bus Station. Various stores selling prasad and other essential puja items will greet you as you approach the hill to the temple. To get to the Naina Devi Temple from other parts of town, take a cab or take a taxi. 7. Kainchi Dham Kanchi Dham, located on the Nainital-Almora route, is a small ashram and Hanuman temple. Kanchi Dham is another name for Neem Karoli Baba Ashram. This beautiful temple was established by Shri Neem Karoli Baba Maharaj Ji, a Hindu Guru. He was a devotee of Lord Hanuman and was known for performing countless miracles during his life. Sri Maa, Neem Karoli Baba's major disciple, currently oversees the ashram, which is only available to guests while she is present. Because it is hidden in the mountains and surrounded by beautiful greenery, Neem Karoli Baba Ashram is the ultimate place to experience silence and peace. This ashram at Kanchi Dham can also accommodate devotees. In the ashram, Hanuman Chalisa is recited numerous times during the day. On June 15, the temple hosts a large fair that residents and foreigners visit annually. 8. Naina Peak Naina Peak, at 2615 meters, is the highest point in Nainital. It is a major tourist attraction of the city and is covered in snow all year. There is a beautiful view from the shade of trees above it. From the top of this peak, you can see the Nanda Devi peak and the mountains of Tibet. The well-known location is one of the most popular vacation destinations in Nainital. The landscape of Naina Peak may be viewed from a variety of perspectives. Aside from trekking, guests may also ride a pony to the top of the mountain. A journey to Nainital isn't complete without walking the 6 kilometres from Mallital to the peak of Naina Peak. The journey is one of the most popular among Nainital visitors. Because Nainital is a hill station, it is best to come during the summer. For tourists, the months of March through June are good for camping and local sightseeing. Naina Peak is around 17 kilometres from Nainital's Tallital Bus Stand. To get to Tallital, take a private or shared cab or passenger car. 9. Bhimtal Lake Bhimtal Lake is one of India's most well-known lakes, located near the city of Bhimtal in the northern Indian state of Uttarakhand. Bhimtal Lake is the largest lake in the Kumaon region, often known as India's Lake District, and serves as a source of drinking water for the city. The lake has been given access to tourists, and various activities occur in and around it. The area around Bhimtal Lake is carefully maintained and offers a nice experience to everyone who visits. Bhimtal Lake Aquarium is on a tiny island in the heart of Bhimtal Lake's beautiful waters. The aquarium contains roughly 12 huge tanks and a variety of species. After the Anglo-Nepal War, the British Raj constructed the Bhimtal Lake Dam in 1883. In the 17th century, Raja Baj Bahadur Chand of the Kumaon Kingdom constructed a shrine on the dam's banks. Boating on the calm waters of Bhimtal Lake is a pastime that everyone should try. The panoramic picture of the lake's beautiful waters beneath lush trees and pure blue skies is magnificent. Boating is accessible daily from 9:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. for INR 150 per person. The picturesque Bhimtal Lake is accessible by private or public transportation from everywhere in Bhimtal. 10. Astronomical Observatory If astronomy is something that fascinates you and is on your wishlist, visits the Nainital Astronomical Observatory. The observatory was established on April 20, 1954. On March 22, 2004, the 50-year-old state observatory at Nainital was renamed ARIES, an acronym for Aryabhatta Research Institute of Observation-Sciences, an independent institute under the Government and Department of Science and Technology. The Aryabhata Research Institute of Observational Science is located 9 kilometres south of the city on Manora Peak, 1951, meters above sea level. Visitors to this Nainital site may observe the Moon, stars, and other celestial bodies through four powerful telescopes. Plan a time window and seek permission from the authorities before visiting this place. 11. Hanuman Garhi About 3.5 kilometres from Nainital. Baba Neem Karoli Ji founded the Hanuman Garhi temple in 1950 AD, which is around 1,951 meters (6,400 feet) above sea level. Along with Hanuman Ji, there are monuments of many other gods and goddesses at the Hanuman Garhi temple, the names of which are mentioned are- Lord Rama, Mata Sita, Shri Krishna Bhagwan, Radha, Lord Shiva, Maa Durga, Sai Baba, Neem Karoli Baba, Vaishno Devi, Mouni Mai, and Shani Dev, among others, are worshipped in the Hanuman Garhi temple. 12. Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple is located in the Nainital district, at the highest point of Mukteshwar city in the Kumaon mountains, at approximately 7,595 feet (2,315 meters above sea level). Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple had a 350-year history when it was known as Lord Shiva, but it is now known as Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple or Mukteshwar Temple. To get the darshan of Lord Shiva built in Mukteshwar Mahadev Temple, you must climb around 100 stairs. 13. Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple Bhimeshwar Mahadev Temple is located around 22 kilometres from Nainital, Uttarakhand. It is situated on the borders of Bhimtal Lake. People believe that Bhima, the most powerful of the Pandavas, established this temple of Lord Shiva after performing penance to Lord Shiva for his clan's name to be remembered for ages. Throughout the year, people go to the temple of Lord Shiva. 14. Jim Corbett National Park Jim Corbett National Park, in Nainital in Uttarakhand, was established in 1936 to save the Bengal Tiger. When Jim Corbett National Park was established in 1936, it was named "Haley National Park." After that, it was renamed Ramganga in 1952 and Jim Corbett National Park in 1956, and this national park was renamed after the hunter and naturalist Jim Corbett The Bengal Tiger, Cheetah, Leopard, Elephant, Bear, Wild Boar, Deer, Sambar, Nilgai, Gharial, Monitor Lizard, Viper, and King Cobra, may be found in Jim Corbett National Park. Many animals may be observed during Jim Corbett National Park vehicle safari. 15. Khurpatal A Khurpatal is also located near Nainital. It is 10 kilometres from Nainital. This lovely little suburb (Khera) is 1635 meters above sea level. The natural beauty of this location captivates everyone. The beautiful lake, surrounding houses, and hotels add to this beauty. Khurpat was famous for producing iron tools until the nineteenth century, but it is now famous for green vegetables. How to Reach Nainital By flight: If you have chosen to take the flight to Nainital, it should be noted that there are no direct flights to Nainital as the nearest airport is 70 kilometres away in Pantnagar. After going to the airport, you can take a taxi or cab to the tourist attraction. By Train: If you've decided to take a train to Nainital, the nearest railway station is Kathgodam, about 23 kilometres away. Regular trains run to Kathgodam from Delhi, Agra, Luckow, Dehradun, Mathura, and other cities in North India. Outside the Kathgodam Railway Station, buses and taxis are available. Every day, many superfast and express trains stop here. By Bus: Nainital has excellent road connectivity to many towns and villages in Northern India. There is a daily bus service from Delhi and Kathgodam to Nainital. The quickest method to go to Nainital is to take an overnight bus from Delhi. This route includes Volvo, AC, and non-AC coaches. Famous Food in Nainital Many different types of Indian food can be found in Nainital, but the most well-known dish in Raas, which is a dish composed of several dishes. Other delicious Nainital desserts include Bawdi Bhatt ki Churani, Aloo Ke Gutka, Arsa Mithai, and Sweet Snack Dumpling. Best Time to Visit Nainital Although tourists can visit Nainital at any time of year, the best time is during the summer, when most of the country experiences serious heat. That is why people like to visit Nainital to avoid the heat. Aside from that, those interested in seeing the snowy environment should visit Nainital between December and February. Next TopicTourist Places in Kottayam ? prev next ? For Videos Join Our Youtube Channel: Join Now Feedback Send your Feedback to [email protected] Help Others, Please Share Learn Latest Tutorials Splunk SPSS Swagger Transact-SQL Tumblr ReactJS Regex Reinforcement Learning R Programming RxJS React Native Python Design Patterns Python Pillow Python Turtle Keras Preparation Aptitude Reasoning Verbal Ability Interview Questions Company Questions Trending Technologies Artificial Intelligence AWS Selenium Cloud Computing Hadoop ReactJS Data Science Angular 7 Blockchain Git Machine Learning DevOps B.Tech / MCA DBMS Data Structures DAA Operating System Computer Network Compiler Design Computer Organization Discrete Mathematics Ethical Hacking Computer Graphics Software Engineering Web Technology Cyber Security Automata C Programming C++ Java .Net Python Prog